Irene Tovar: "The greatest enemy of poverty is education. The future of California depends on how we educate our citizens."
Susana Amezcua: "As a future teacher, I don't want to give my students false hope about their chances of going to college in CA."
Susana Amezcua: "CSUN became my home. My little brother might not have the same opportunities that I did if impaction continues."
Susana Amezcua: "I'm a daughter of two farm workers from Ventura County, a county which CSUN will now exclude as a local service area."
Dr. Perez: "Institutions serving those w/most need should receive additional support from the state similar to how K-12 schools are funded."
Dr. Perez: "Majority of public higher education institutions in CA are Hispanic Serving Institutions. 2/3 of all students attend HSIs."
Dr. Perez: "What the state calls growth, we call restoration. Disinvestment has led to many opportunities lost for students."
@ADCollegeOpp: "We fundamentally don't have a system that can accommodate eligible students in CA's four-year institutions."
@ADCollegeOpp: "Master Plan for CA higher ed says we all have a spot in our universities, but in reality we don't."
Panelists: @ADCollegeOpp (VP of @CollegeOpp), Dr. Monte Perez (Pres. of LA Mission College), & Susana Amezcua (CSUN alum), & Irene Tovar
Jorge Haynes: "I've never met a campus president or faculty member who wanted impaction. Nobody wants impaction."
Jorge Haynes: "Only way to resolve the issue is to provide sufficient funding to match student demand for higher education in California"
Jorge Haynes: "$6,600 per student allocated for CSU system now, down from over $10,000 per student"
Jorge Haynes, former member of CSU Chancellor's Office director of external affairs, says CSUs had to respond to more apps & less funding
